		<div id="siteNotice"><script type='text/javascript'>if (wgNotice != '') document.writeln(wgNotice);</script></div>		<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">Pidgin</h1>
		<div id="bodyContent">
			<h3 id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</h3>
			<div id="contentSub"></div>
									<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="#searchInput">search</a></div>			<!-- start content -->
			<div class="dablink">This article is about simplified languages.  For the instant messaging client, see <a href="/wiki/Pidgin_(software)" title="Pidgin (software)">Pidgin (software)</a>.  For other uses, see <a href="/wiki/Pidgin_(disambiguation)" title="Pidgin (disambiguation)">Pidgin (disambiguation)</a>.</div>
<p>A <b>pidgin</b> is a simplified language that develops as a means of communication between two or more groups that do not have a language in common, in situations such as <a href="/wiki/Trade" title="Trade">trade</a>. Pidgins are not the native language of any speech community, but are instead learned as second languages.<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup> Pidgins usually have low <a href="/wiki/Prestige_(sociology)" title="Prestige (sociology)">prestige</a> with respect to other languages.<sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2" title=""><span>[</span>3<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>Not all simplified or "broken" forms of language (<a href="/wiki/Patois" title="Patois">patois</a>) are pidgins. Pidgins have their own norms of usage which must be learned to speak the pidgin well.<sup id="cite_ref-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-3" title=""><span>[</span>4<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
